63.1 The R Concept
if evaluates a single logical condition and runs a block of code only if that condition is TRUE; an optional else provides an alternative block for when it’s FALSE:
This is a genuinely different tool from the vectorized comparisons you’ve used throughout this level (df$col &gt;= 130, applied to every row at once). if expects a single TRUE or FALSE value — not a whole vector — and controls which block of code runs, rather than producing a new column of results.

if (condition) {
  # runs only if condition is TRUE
} else {
  # runs only if condition is FALSE
}

if (nrow(participants) == 100) {
  print("Enrollment complete")
} else {
  print("Still recruiting")
}

